<span class="displaytext"><i> excerpts from: </i> <p><i> clemson university news release </i> </p><p><i> palmetto poll places (candidate last), (candidate last) in dead heat </i> </p><p>clemson - the clemson university palmetto poll of likely voters in the south carolina (PARTY NAME) and (PARTY NAME) presidential primaries finds (candidate full) and (candidate full) in a virtual dead heat in the gop contest, 19 percent to 18 percent, respectively... </p><p>the poll also finds only about one-quarter of the voters in each party admit to having a good idea about who they will support in the (PARTY NAME) primary on jan. 19, 2008, or the (PARTY NAME) primary scheduled for jan. 29, 2008. (see the full results of the poll in <a href="http://www.clemson.edu/newsroom/special_reports/internal/poll_answers.doc" target="_blank">word</a> format or <a href="http://www.clemson.edu/newsroom/special_reports/internal/poll_details.htm" target="_blank">html</a> format). </p><p>"the fact that (candidate full), who has just now announced for the race, is virtually tied with (candidate last) means that the (PARTY NAME)s are searching for an alternative to the familiar candidates," said clemson university strom thurmond professor of political science david woodard. "the number of undecided voters means that the race in south carolina will be hotly contested, and the outcome decisive in the national races." </p><p>the battle for the (PARTY NAME) primary is perched for a shakeup in the fall, according to bruce ransom, clemson university political scientist. </p><p>"the poll finds (candidate full) and (candidate full) virtual tied just prior to (candidate last)'s official entry into the (PARTY NAME) primary, giving (candidate last) an opportunity to enter the race officially and gather support from social conservatives, allowing him to distance himself from (candidate last) and the other top-tier candidates," ransom said. </p><p>... </p><p>four hundred respondents were interviewed in each party for a total of 800 respondents. the poll has a margin of error of plus or minus 4.9 percent in each party subgroup. </p><p>... </p><p><i> to view complete article, please visit: </i> </p><p><a href="http://www.clemson.edu/newsroom/articles/top-stories/palmettopoll.php5"> http://www.clemson.edu/newsroom/articles/top-stories/palmettopoll.php5 </a></p></span>



